    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Senate Energy Bill</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from National Mining Assn president Jack Gerard says proposed energy legislation will help US coal industry</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Before weighing the merits of the energy bill being considered by the Senate (editorial, May 12), your readers should also know other facts.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Before weighing the merits of the energy bill being considered by the Senate (editorial, May 12), your readers should also know other facts.</p>
        <p>First, the bill enables our nation to rely more on a domestic energy reserve larger than the world's proved oil -- our 274 billion tons of coal. Official estimates say each ton equals up to 4.5 barrels of oil.</p>
        <p>Next, its coal-specific provisions promote higher efficiency in power generation; lower national carbon intensity (for global warming); and the long-term availability of a reliable and reliably low-cost source of energy for our nation.</p>
        <p>Finally, its research provisions ultimately support the initiative to vanquish carbon altogether with the hydrogen economy. Such things considered, your readers may conclude that this bill should be passed.</p>
        <p>JACK GERARD  Pres., National Mining Assn.  Washington, May 12, 2003</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
